      {"question_id":"dl_int_002","type":"scenario","question":"A CNN classifies images but performs poorly on slightly rotated versions. What is the BEST training strategy?","options":["Use a larger model","Apply data augmentation with rotations during training","Increase learning rate","Use a different loss function"],"correct_answer":1,"explanation":"Data augmentation introduces rotated, flipped, and cropped versions of training images, teaching the model to be invariant to these transformations. This is more effective than changing architecture or hyperparameters for geometric invariance.","difficulty_score":5,"time_seconds":75,"tags":["CNN","data_augmentation","invariance","computer_vision"],"prerequisites":["dl_beg_002"],"common_mistakes":["Adding more model capacity instead of fixing data distribution"],"learning_resources":["https://pytorch.org/vision/stable/transforms.html"],"real_world_context":"Data augmentation is mandatory in medical imaging where geometric invariance is critical."},
